NT||cp|8|AT|^B@2^Y@3^*Bhondo717: ^*N|cp||at|If Marge were on lead against 1N, the standard lead from KJ10 is the J. Some people play "coded 10s and 9s" to address the following issue. The standard lead from AJ10 and KJ10 is the J. Further, the standard lead from J10 is also the J. So, partner is not sure when you lead the J whether or not you have the A or K. One way to solve that is to play coded 10s. If you play coded 10s, then the lead of the 10 shows one of two possible holdings--it either shows the broken sequence AJ10 or KJ10 or it is top of nothing, 109. Partner can usually work out which it is, as the J is often visible when partner leads the 10 from 109.|
PG| ***** 94 ***** |


NT||cp|8|AT|^B@2^Y@3^*Bhondo717: ^*N|cp||at|So, that is why people play "coded 10s" to differentiate between AJ10 and KJ10. If you play that then the lead of the J denies a higher honor. Also coded 10s only apply when defending NT. Some people shorthand coded 10s by saying the 10 shows 0 or two higher. That is correct, but not complete because for example if you have AQ10x you do not lead the 10, even though you have 2 higher.|
PG| ***** 95 ***** |


NT||cp|8|AT|^B@2^Y@3^*Bhondo717: ^*N|cp||at|So, coded 10s show either a broken sequence or nothing higher than the 10. Similarly, you can play "coded 9s." Then you lead 9 from Q109 K109 or A109 and you lead 9 from 9xx. Therefore, the 9 shows a broken sequence with the 10, or nothing higher. One other point. From QJ10 you still lead the Q, not the 10 because that is not the broken sequence of AJ10 or KJ10. The Q is clear, it shows a sequence headed by the Q. If you are still not clear on the concept of coded 10s and 9s, you can read my opening leads tutorial or write to me.|
